{"title_page": "Joe Biden sexual assault allegation", "text_new": "<noinclude>{{User:RMCD bot/subject notice|1=?|2=Talk:Joe Biden sexual assault allegation#Requested move 14 April 2020 }}\n</noinclude><!-- Please do not remove or change this AfD message until the discussion has been closed. -->\n{{Article for deletion/dated|page=Joe Biden assault allegation|timestamp=20200412194501|year=2020|month=April|day=12|substed=yes|help=off}}\n<!-- Once discussion is closed, please place on talk page: {{Old AfD multi|page=Joe Biden assault allegation|date=12 April 2020|result='''keep'''}} -->\n<!-- End of AfD message, feel free to edit beyond this point -->\n{{Redirect|Tara Reade|the actress|Tara Reid}}\n{{Use American English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n[[File:SenareaidIDTaraReade.webp|thumb|Portrait of Reade on her U.S. Senate ID (provided by her to ''[[New York Times]]'')]]\nIn April 2020, Tara Reade alleged that [[Joe Biden]] had sexually assaulted her when she was a senate aide in 1993.<ref name=InterceptTimesup>{{cite news |url=https://theintercept.com/2020/03/24/joe-biden-metoo-times-up/ |first=Ryan |last=Grim |title=Time's Up Said It Could Not Fund a #MeToo Allegation Against Joe Biden, Citing Its Nonprofit Status and His Presidential Run |website=[[The Intercept]] |date=March 24, 2020 |access-date=April 9, 2020 }}</ref><ref name=vox>{{cite news |url=https://www.vox.com/2020/3/27/21195935/joe-biden-sexual-assault-allegation |last=North |first=Anna |title=A sexual assault allegation against Joe Biden has ignited a firestorm of controversy |website=[[Vox (website)|Vox]] |date=March 27, 2020 |access-date=April 9, 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://thehill.com/hilltv/rising/489719-tara-reade-discusses-biden-allegation-with-hilltvs-rising |title=Tara Reade discusses Biden allegation with Hill.TV's 'Rising' |newspaper=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]|date=March 26, 2020 |access-date=April 9, 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/news/rose-mcgowan-alyssa-milano-joe-biden-alexandra-tara-reade-kavanaugh-a9454256.html |last=White |first=Adam |title=Rose McGowan calls Charmed co-star Alyssa Milano 'a fraud' for endorsing Joe Biden |newspaper=[[The Independent]] |date=April 8, 2020 <!-- From the timestamp in the HTML source --> |access-date=April 9, 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Halper|first=Katie|url=https://www.currentaffairs.org/2020/03/tara-reade-tells-her-story|title=Tara Reade Tells Her Story|date=March 31, 2020|magazine=[[Current Affairs (magazine)|Current Affairs]]|access-date=April 9, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> A Biden spokesperson said the allegation was false.<ref name=nyt>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/12/us/politics/joe-biden-tara-reade-sexual-assault-complaint.html |last=Lerer |first=Lisa |last2=Ember |first2=Sydney |title=Examining Tara Reade's Sexual Assault Allegation Against Joe Biden |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=April 12, 2020 |access-date=April 12, 2020 }}</ref>\n\n==Allegations==\nIn April 2019, Reade made her accusation after seeing an episode of the ''[[The View (talk show)|The View]]'' where the panelists seemed to take Biden's side over Nevada lawmaker [[Lucy Flores]] who had accused Biden of inappropriate touching.<ref name=InterceptTimesup/> Reade's initial statement only alleged inappropriate touching and sexual harassment but did not mention assault.<ref name=InterceptTimesup/><ref>{{Cite news|first=Alan  |last=Riquelmy |authorlink=   |title= Nevada County woman says Joe Biden inappropriately touched her while working in his U.S. Senate office  |newspaper=[[The Union (newspaper)|The Union]]|date= April 3, 2019|url=https://www.theunion.com/news/nevada-county-woman-says-joe-biden-inappropriately-touched-her-while-working-in-his-u-s-senate-office/ |accessdate=}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2020, Reade accused Biden of pushing her against a wall and digitally penetrating her in 1993 in a [[Capitol Hill]] office building.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.salon.com/2020/03/31/a-woman-accuses-joe-biden-of-sexual-assault-and-all-hell-breaks-loose-online-heres-what-we-know/|title=A woman accuses Joe Biden of sexual assault, and all hell breaks loose online. Here's what we know|last=Marcotte|first=Amanda|date=March 31, 2020|website=Salon|language=en|url-status=live|access-date=April 15, 2020}}</ref> She filed a public incident report with the Washington, D.C., police on April 9, 2020. The report does not mention Biden, but in Reade's interview with ''[[The New York Times]]'' she confirmed that the complaint was about him.<ref name=nyt /> She acknowledged that the statute of limitations has lapsed, and that she filed the report \"for safety reasons only\".<ref name=vox /><ref name=\"nyt\" /> According to Reade, the incident happened during March, April, or May of 1993.<ref name=Mangan-200414>{{cite news | url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/04/14/joe-biden-accused-of-sex-assault-amid-challenge-to-donald-trump.html | title=Joe Biden is accused of sexual assault as he heads toward election fight with Trump | work=[[CNBC]] | date=April 14, 2020 | accessdate=April 15, 2020 | first=Dan | last=Mangan}}</ref>\n\nOn April 12, 2020, ''The New York Times'' released an analysis of their investigative reporting in which they interviewed Reade, several of her friends, lawyers, nearly two dozen people who worked with Biden in the early 1990s, and the seven women who accused Biden of kissing, hugging, or touching them in ways that had made them feel uncomfortable. No other allegations about sexual assault surfaced in the course of this reporting, nor did any former Biden staff members corroborate any details of Reade's allegation, although several of the seven women stated that they believed Reade.<ref name=\"nyt\" /> Two friends of Reade confirmed to ''The New York Times'' that she had told them of the alleged assault (one in 1993 shortly after the alleged assault took place, the other in 2008); and Reade's brother has publicly stated that she had told him about it.<ref name=\"nyt\" />\n\n==Media coverage==\nOn April 13, [[Dean Baquet]], executive editor of ''The New York Times,'' published  an [[op-ed]] responding to various criticisms including that his newspaper was slow to publish coverage of the news story.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationalreview.com/2020/04/the-new-york-times-denies-tara-reade-the-christine-blasey-ford-treatment/|title=The New York Times Denies Tara Reade the Christine Blasey Ford Treatment|date=April 14, 2020|website=National Review|language=en-US|access-date=April 15, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://slate.com/news-and-politics/2020/04/joe-biden-harassment-nytimes.html|title=Joe Biden Sails Under the New York Times' Bar for Sexual Abuse|last=Cauterucci|first=Christina|date=April 13, 2020|website=Slate Magazine|language=en|access-date=April 15, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2020/04/media-floodgates-open-joe-biden-tara-reade-allegation|title=The Media Floodgates Finally Open on Biden Sexual Assault Allegation|last=Ecarma|first=Caleb|website=Vanity Fair|language=en|access-date=April 15, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|last=Smith|first=Ben|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/13/business/media/joe-biden-tara-reade-new-york-times.html|title=The Times Took 19 Days to Report an Accusation Against Biden. Here's Why.|date=April 13, 2020|work=The New York Times|access-date=April 15, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> In an interview with the newspaper's media columnist [[Ben Smith (journalist)|Ben Smith]], Baquet responded to a controversy about a line in the news story that was removed after the piece's initial publication. The sentence previously read: \"The Times found no pattern of sexual misconduct by Mr. Biden, beyond the hugs, kisses and touching that women previously said made them uncomfortable.\" Baquet explained that it had been included originally in order not to falsely imply that other individuals had made allegations of as invasive in nature as Reade's but thereafter removed because of \"awkward phrasing issue that could be read different ways.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/media/492680-ny-times-faces-blowback-for-removal-of-controversial-passage-on-biden-sexual|title=NY Times faces blowback for removal of controversial passage on Biden sexual assault allegation|last=Swanson|first=Ian|date=April 14, 2020|website=The Hill|access-date=April 15, 2020}}</ref> Baquet stated that this edit was made after [[Joe Biden 2020 presidential campaign|the Biden campaign]] had objected to it.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Reactions ==\nThe chief and deputy-chief of Biden's Senate staff during 1992 and 1993 as well as its long-term executive assistant, interviewed for the original piece within the ''New York Times,'' expressed their doubts as to the veracity of Reade's account, arguing that that they would have recalled Reade's complaints about Biden's conduct had she made them and asserted that the behavior alleged would be out of character for him. Melissa Lefko, then a staff assistant for Biden, told the ''Times'' that she had never experienced harassment and Biden's office was a \"very supportive environment for women.\" \"When you work on the Hill, everyone knows who the good guys are and who the bad guys are, and Biden was a good guy.\"<ref>https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/12/us/politics/joe-biden-tara-reade-sexual-assault-complaint.html</ref>\n\nOn April 14, 2020, in an online conversation with [[The Wing (workspace)|The Wing]], [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] [[Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez]] said that it was legitimate to discuss Reade's allegation against Joe Biden.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/alexandria-ocasio-cortez-joe-biden-its-legitimate-to-talk-about-allegations/|title=Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez: \"It's legitimate to talk about\" allegations against Joe Biden|website=www.cbsnews.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/alexandria-ocasio-cortez-sexual-assault-allegation-joe-biden-news-a9466051.html|title=AOC says it's 'legitimate to talk about' sexual assault allegation against Joe Biden|date=2020-04-15|website=The Independent|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Cite web|first=Katie |last=Halper |authorlink=   |title= Biden accuser: \"I wanted to be a senator; I didn't want to sleep with one\" (audio) |website=Katie Halper podcast|date=March 30, 2020 |url=https://soundcloud.com/katie-halper/tara-to-post  |accessdate=}}\n{{Joe Biden}}\n\n[[Category:2020 controversies]]\n[[Category:April 2020 events in the United States]]\n[[Category:Sexual assaults in the United States]]\n[[Category:Media-related controversies in the United States]]\n[[Category:Joe Biden 2020 presidential campaign|Assault allegation]]\n", "text_old": "<noinclude>{{User:RMCD bot/subject notice|1=?|2=Talk:Joe Biden sexual assault allegation#Requested move 14 April 2020 }}\n</noinclude><!-- Please do not remove or change this AfD message until the discussion has been closed. -->\n{{Article for deletion/dated|page=Joe Biden assault allegation|timestamp=20200412194501|year=2020|month=April|day=12|substed=yes|help=off}}\n<!-- Once discussion is closed, please place on talk page: {{Old AfD multi|page=Joe Biden assault allegation|date=12 April 2020|result='''keep'''}} -->\n<!-- End of AfD message, feel free to edit beyond this point -->\n{{Redirect|Tara Reade|the actress|Tara Reid}}\n{{Use American English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n[[File:SenareaidIDTaraReade.webp|thumb|Portrait of Reade on her U.S. Senate ID (provided by her to ''[[New York Times]]'')]]\nIn April 2020, Tara Reade alleged that [[Joe Biden]] had sexually assaulted her when she was a senate aide in 1993.<ref name=InterceptTimesup>{{cite news |url=https://theintercept.com/2020/03/24/joe-biden-metoo-times-up/ |first=Ryan |last=Grim |title=Time's Up Said It Could Not Fund a #MeToo Allegation Against Joe Biden, Citing Its Nonprofit Status and His Presidential Run |website=[[The Intercept]] |date=March 24, 2020 |access-date=April 9, 2020 }}</ref><ref name=vox>{{cite news |url=https://www.vox.com/2020/3/27/21195935/joe-biden-sexual-assault-allegation |last=North |first=Anna |title=A sexual assault allegation against Joe Biden has ignited a firestorm of controversy |website=[[Vox (website)|Vox]] |date=March 27, 2020 |access-date=April 9, 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://thehill.com/hilltv/rising/489719-tara-reade-discusses-biden-allegation-with-hilltvs-rising |title=Tara Reade discusses Biden allegation with Hill.TV's 'Rising' |newspaper=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]|date=March 26, 2020 |access-date=April 9, 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/news/rose-mcgowan-alyssa-milano-joe-biden-alexandra-tara-reade-kavanaugh-a9454256.html |last=White |first=Adam |title=Rose McGowan calls Charmed co-star Alyssa Milano 'a fraud' for endorsing Joe Biden |newspaper=[[The Independent]] |date=April 8, 2020 <!-- From the timestamp in the HTML source --> |access-date=April 9, 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Halper|first=Katie|url=https://www.currentaffairs.org/2020/03/tara-reade-tells-her-story|title=Tara Reade Tells Her Story|date=March 31, 2020|magazine=[[Current Affairs (magazine)|Current Affairs]]|access-date=April 9, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> A Biden spokesperson said the allegation was false.<ref name=nyt>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/12/us/politics/joe-biden-tara-reade-sexual-assault-complaint.html |last=Lerer |first=Lisa |last2=Ember |first2=Sydney |title=Examining Tara Reade's Sexual Assault Allegation Against Joe Biden |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=April 12, 2020 |access-date=April 12, 2020 }}</ref>\n\n==Allegations==\nIn April 2019, Reade made her accusation after seeing an episode of the ''[[The View (talk show)|The View]]'' where the panelists seemed to take Biden's side over Nevada lawmaker [[Lucy Flores]] who had accused Biden of inappropriate touching.<ref name=InterceptTimesup/> Reade's initial statement only alleged inappropriate touching and sexual harassment but did not mention assault.<ref name=InterceptTimesup/><ref>{{Cite news|first=Alan  |last=Riquelmy |authorlink=   |title= Nevada County woman says Joe Biden inappropriately touched her while working in his U.S. Senate office  |newspaper=[[The Union (newspaper)|The Union]]|date= April 3, 2019|url=https://www.theunion.com/news/nevada-county-woman-says-joe-biden-inappropriately-touched-her-while-working-in-his-u-s-senate-office/ |accessdate=}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2020, Reade accused Biden of pushing her against a wall and digitally penetrating her in 1993 in a [[Capitol Hill]] office building.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.salon.com/2020/03/31/a-woman-accuses-joe-biden-of-sexual-assault-and-all-hell-breaks-loose-online-heres-what-we-know/|title=A woman accuses Joe Biden of sexual assault, and all hell breaks loose online. Here's what we know|last=Marcotte|first=Amanda|date=March 31, 2020|website=Salon|language=en|url-status=live|access-date=April 15, 2020}}</ref> She filed a public incident report with the Washington, D.C., police on April 9, 2020. The report does not mention Biden, but in Reade's interview with ''[[The New York Times]]'' she confirmed that the complaint was about him.<ref name=nyt /> She acknowledged that the statute of limitations has lapsed, and that she filed the report \"for safety reasons only\".<ref name=vox /><ref name=\"nyt\" /> According to Reade, the incident happened during March, April, or May of 1993.<ref name=Mangan-200414>{{cite news | url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/04/14/joe-biden-accused-of-sex-assault-amid-challenge-to-donald-trump.html | title=Joe Biden is accused of sexual assault as he heads toward election fight with Trump | work=[[CNBC]] | date=April 14, 2020 | accessdate=April 15, 2020 | first=Dan | last=Mangan}}</ref>\n\nOn April 12, 2020, ''The New York Times'' released an analysis of their investigative reporting in which they interviewed Reade, several of her friends, lawyers, nearly two dozen people who worked with Biden in the early 1990s, and the seven women who accused Biden of kissing, hugging, or touching them in ways that had made them feel uncomfortable. No other allegations about sexual assault surfaced in the course of this reporting, nor did any former Biden staff members corroborate any details of Reade's allegation, although several of the seven women stated that they believed Reade.<ref name=\"nyt\" /> Two friends of Reade confirmed to ''The New York Times'' that she had told them of the alleged assault (one in 1993 shortly after the alleged assault took place, the other in 2008); and Reade's brother has publicly stated that she had told him about it.<ref name=\"nyt\" />\n\n==Media coverage==\nOn April 13, [[Dean Baquet]], executive editor of ''The New York Times,'' published  an [[op-ed]] responding to various criticisms including that his newspaper was slow to publish coverage of the news story.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationalreview.com/2020/04/the-new-york-times-denies-tara-reade-the-christine-blasey-ford-treatment/|title=The New York Times Denies Tara Reade the Christine Blasey Ford Treatment|date=April 14, 2020|website=National Review|language=en-US|access-date=April 15, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://slate.com/news-and-politics/2020/04/joe-biden-harassment-nytimes.html|title=Joe Biden Sails Under the New York Times' Bar for Sexual Abuse|last=Cauterucci|first=Christina|date=April 13, 2020|website=Slate Magazine|language=en|access-date=April 15, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2020/04/media-floodgates-open-joe-biden-tara-reade-allegation|title=The Media Floodgates Finally Open on Biden Sexual Assault Allegation|last=Ecarma|first=Caleb|website=Vanity Fair|language=en|access-date=April 15, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|last=Smith|first=Ben|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/13/business/media/joe-biden-tara-reade-new-york-times.html|title=The Times Took 19 Days to Report an Accusation Against Biden. Here's Why.|date=April 13, 2020|work=The New York Times|access-date=April 15, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> In an interview with the newspaper's media columnist [[Ben Smith (journalist)|Ben Smith]], Baquet responded to a controversy about a line in the news story that was removed after the piece's initial publication. The sentence previously read: \"The Times found no pattern of sexual misconduct by Mr. Biden, beyond the hugs, kisses and touching that women previously said made them uncomfortable.\" Baquet explained that it had been included originally in order not to falsely imply that other individuals had made allegations of as invasive in nature as Reade's but thereafter removed because of \"awkward phrasing issue that could be read different ways.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/media/492680-ny-times-faces-blowback-for-removal-of-controversial-passage-on-biden-sexual|title=NY Times faces blowback for removal of controversial passage on Biden sexual assault allegation|last=Swanson|first=Ian|date=April 14, 2020|website=The Hill|access-date=April 15, 2020}}</ref> Baquet stated that this edit was made after [[Joe Biden 2020 presidential campaign|the Biden campaign]] had objected to it.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Reactions ==\nThe chief and deputy-chief of Biden's Senate staff during 1992 and 1993 as well as its long-term executive assistant, interviewed for the original piece within the ''New York Times,'' expressed their doubts as to the veracity of Reade's account, arguing that that they would have recalled Reade's complaints about Biden's conduct had she made them and asserted that the behavior alleged would be out of character for him. Melissa Lefko, then a staff assistant for Biden, told the ''Times'' that she had never experienced harassment and Biden's office was a \"very supportive environment for women.\" \"When you work on the Hill, everyone knows who the good guys are and who the bad guys are, and Biden was a good guy.\"<ref>https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/12/us/politics/joe-biden-tara-reade-sexual-assault-complaint.html</ref>\n\nOn April 14, 2020, in an online conversation with The Wing, [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] [[Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez]] said that it was legitimate to discuss Reade's allegation against Joe Biden.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/alexandria-ocasio-cortez-joe-biden-its-legitimate-to-talk-about-allegations/|title=Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez: \"It's legitimate to talk about\" allegations against Joe Biden|website=www.cbsnews.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/alexandria-ocasio-cortez-sexual-assault-allegation-joe-biden-news-a9466051.html|title=AOC says it's 'legitimate to talk about' sexual assault allegation against Joe Biden|date=2020-04-15|website=The Independent|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Cite web|first=Katie |last=Halper |authorlink=   |title= Biden accuser: \"I wanted to be a senator; I didn't want to sleep with one\" (audio) |website=Katie Halper podcast|date=March 30, 2020 |url=https://soundcloud.com/katie-halper/tara-to-post  |accessdate=}}\n{{Joe Biden}}\n\n[[Category:2020 controversies]]\n[[Category:April 2020 events in the United States]]\n[[Category:Sexual assaults in the United States]]\n[[Category:Media-related controversies in the United States]]\n[[Category:Joe Biden 2020 presidential campaign|Assault allegation]]\n", "name_user": "RedHotPear", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReactions:link needed for obscure entity", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joe_Biden_sexual_assault_allegation"}
{"title_page": "British Lion (album)", "text_new": "= [[British Lion (Band)|British Lion]] =\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = British Lion\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Steve Harris (musician)|Steve Harris]]\n| cover      = Steve Harris - British Lion.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = 24 September 2012\n| recorded   = \n| venue      =\n| studio     = *Monkey Puzzle, Suffolk, UK <small>(drum & vocal tracks 2, 4, 9)</small>\n*Purple Studio, Norwich, UK <small>(drum & vocal tracks 1, 2 7)</small>\n*BL Studios, Harlow, UK <small>(back tracks & vocal track 10)</small>\n*Barnyard Studios, Harlow, Essex <small>(back tracks)</small>\n*Algarve Studio, Faro, Portugal <small>(back tracks)</small>\n| genre      = [[Hard rock]]<ref name=\"kerrang lion\">{{cite journal | title = Beyond the Beast | journal = [[Kerrang!]] | date = 15 September 2012 | first = George | last = Garner | issue = 1432 | pages = 22\u201327}}</ref>\n| length     = 52:11\n| label      = *[[EMI]] <small>(International edition)</small>\n*[[Universal Music Enterprises|UME]] <small>(US edition)</small>\n| producer   = [[Steve Harris (musician)|Steve Harris]]\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title = [[The Burning (British Lion album)|The Burning]]\n| next_year  = 2020\n}}\n[[British Lion (Band)|British Lion]] released their album with [[Steve Harris (musician)|Steve Harris]], best known as the bassist and primary songwriter for the British heavy metal band [[Iron Maiden]]. The album was announced on 18 July 2012 and released on 24 September.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.metalhammer.co.uk/news/iron-maidens-steve-harris-announces-first-ever-solo-album-british-lion/ |title=Iron Maiden's Steve Harris Announces First Ever Solo Album ''British Lion'' |magazine=[[Metal Hammer]] |date=18 July 2012 |accessdate=18 July 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140223010938/http://www.metalhammer.co.uk/news/iron-maidens-steve-harris-announces-first-ever-solo-album-british-lion/ |archivedate=23 February 2014 }}</ref>\n\n[[British Lion (Band)|British Lion]] announced their second album titled '''''The Burning''''' on the 31st of October 2019 and released it on the 17th of January 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.loudersound.com/news/steve-harriss-british-lion-announce-second-album-the-burning|title=Steve Harris's British Lion announce second album The Burning|last=October 2019|first=Fraser Lewry31|website=Classic Rock Magazine|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the release of '''''The Burning''''', critics published reviews on their thoughts of the album. '''Metal Planet Music''' voiced that \"the first thing that strikes you is the music, great hard rock with melody and class, but it\u2019s the heart and emotion that will stay with you long after the last note rings out. Coming eight years after their debut, \u2018'''''The Burning'''''\u2019 is the second album by [[British Lion (Band)|British Lion]] and the [[Steve Harris (musician)|Steve Harris]] led quintet have made a record that is at once modern, nostalgic and timeless\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://metalplanetmusic.com/2020/01/gig-review-british-lion-the-burning/|title=Album Review : British Lion \u2013 \u2018The Burning|last=Authoradmin|date=2020-01-22|website=Metal Planet Music|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\n[[Kerrang!]] mainly spoke upon the vocals of the album stating that \"the band\u2019s debut was rather a baptism of fire for singer '''Richard Taylor''', who had to weather some predictable yet redundant criticisms comparing him to [[Bruce Dickinson]] from Steve\u2019s \u201cother\u201d band. He sings like he has a point to prove throughout '''''The Burning'''''. A telling sign of the frontman\u2019s burgeoning confidence comes on '''Elysium''' \u2013 a song that boasts a killer chorus but an even better final passage, as he belts out a series of absolutely massive sustained notes over a swelling choral section. Equally impressive is his ability to extract emotion from a song. Whether he\u2019s communing with lost souls on '''Lightning''' or offering a consolatory ear on closer '''Native Son''', he often brings a moving sense of fragility to the fore. Clearly, this particular lion has more at its disposal than claws alone\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kerrang.com/reviews/album-review-british-lion-the-burning/|title=Album Review: British Lion \u2013 The Burning|website=Kerrang!|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\n=[[British Lion (Band)|British Lion Band]]=\nFollowing the initial announcement of the album's release in July 2012, ''[[Classic Rock (magazine)|Classic Rock]]'' revealed that the project originated with a band, named [[British Lion (Band)|British Lion]], which Harris had been mentoring in the early 1990s.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.classicrockmagazine.com/news/maidens-harris-announces-solo-album/ |title=Maiden's Harris announces solo album |accessdate=8 September 2012 |last=Kielty |first=Martin |date=18 July 2012 |magazine=[[Classic Rock (magazine)|Classic Rock]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130119104531/http://www.classicrockmagazine.com/news/maidens-harris-announces-solo-album/ |archivedate=19 January 2013 }}</ref> Harris confirmed this during an interview with ''Classic Rock'' the following month, explaining that he became involved after \"Graham Leslie [guitar] came to me with a cassette of songs... and I thought they were really good, so I said I\u2019d try to help his band do something. I ended up managing them and producing them and writing with them.\"<ref name=\"CRAugust\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.classicrockmagazine.com/features/iron-maidens-steve-harris-on-british-lion-solo-project/ |title=Exclusive: Iron Maiden\u2019s Steve Harris talks about his British Lion solo project |accessdate=8 September 2012 |last=Brannigan |first=Paul |date=27 August 2012 |magazine=[[Classic Rock (magazine)|Classic Rock]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131020112709/http://www.classicrockmagazine.com/features/iron-maidens-steve-harris-on-british-lion-solo-project/ |archivedate=20 October 2013 }}</ref> After the original band split up, he \"kept in touch with Richie [Taylor, vocals] and Graham, and then Richie was working with another guitarist called David Hawkins, who's a really talented guy, and so we started writing songs together.\"<ref name=\"CRAugust\"/> After several years of work, due to Harris being occupied with Iron Maiden, the album ultimately consists of \"six songs written with Richie and David, there's one with just me and Richie, and the others are me, Richie, Graham and a couple of other guys that were around at the time.\"<ref name=\"CRAugust\"/> In an interview published by ''[[Kerrang!]]'' in September, Harris said that he considers [[British Lion (Band)|British Lion]] \"more of a side-project\" than a solo record.<ref name=\"kerrang lion\"/>\n\nStylistically, Harris argues that the record is \"more mainstream rock than metal, very British sounding, very 70s-influenced and quite commercial\u2026 but good commercial. There's all kinds of stuff going on, with nods to [[the Who]] and [[UFO (band)|UFO]] and some classic British rock bands, but it's not the progressive rock album some might be expecting.\"<ref name=\"CRAugust\"/> During his appearance on ''[[That Metal Show]]'' in September 2012, Harris revealed that he tried a number of bass-playing techniques which he would not do with Iron Maiden, such as letting his strings \"go dead\".<ref>{{cite episode | title = Iron Maiden | series = [[That Metal Show]] | serieslink =  | credits = [[Eddie Trunk]], [[Jim Florentine]], [[Don Jamieson (comedian)|Don Jamieson]] (starring) | network = [[VH1 Classic]] | station = | location = Los Angeles | airdate = 22 September 2012}}</ref>\n\nHarris stated that he intends to tour the release at some stage, remarking that, although \"there are no shows arranged yet\", \"I know we\u2019ll be playing clubs, which is great because I\u2019ve not played clubs for years\", and that he intends to release a follow up album in the future.<ref name=\"CRAugust\"/> A European club tour, taking place in February and March, was eventually announced on 10 January 2013.<ref>{{cite web|last=Kielty |first=Martin |title=Steve Harris announces solo UK tour |url=http://www.classicrockmagazine.com/news/iron-maiden-steve-harris-announces-solo-uk-tour/ |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130215175706/http://www.classicrockmagazine.com/news/iron-maiden-steve-harris-announces-solo-uk-tour/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=15 February 2013 |work=[[Classic Rock (magazine)|Classic Rock]] |accessdate=10 January 2013 |date=10 January 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Iron Maiden's Steve Harris Taking ''British Lion'' On The Road \u2013 \"It's Exciting, Going Back to the Roots, And It's Going To Be Fantastic\"|url=http://www.bravewords.com/news/196789|work=[[Brave Words & Bloody Knuckles]]|accessdate=10 January 2013|date=10 January 2013}}</ref>\n\nA music video for the song \"This Is My God\" was released on 2 October 2012,<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.classicrockmagazine.com/music_and_videos/steve-harris-reveals-his-god/ |title=Steve Harris reveals his God |accessdate=2 October 2012 |last=Kielty |first=Martin |date=2 October 2012 |magazine=[[Classic Rock (magazine)|Classic Rock]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121006025045/http://www.classicrockmagazine.com/music_and_videos/steve-harris-reveals-his-god/ |archivedate=6 October 2012 }}</ref> followed by a video for \"Us Against the World\" on 28 November.<ref>{{cite news|title=Iron Maiden Bassist Releases 'Us Against The World' Video|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=182906|work=[[Blabbermouth.net]]|accessdate=28 November 2012|date=28 November 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\n{{Album ratings\n| MC = 56/100<ref name=\"meta\">{{cite web| title = ''British Lion'' Reviews, Ratings, Credits, and More| work = [[Metacritic]]| publisher = [[CBS Interactive]]| url = http://www.metacritic.com/music/british-lion| accessdate = 16 August 2013}}</ref>\n| rev1 = [[About.com]]\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref name=\"About.com\">{{cite web | url = http://heavymetal.about.com/od/cdreviews/fr/Steve-Harris-British-Lion-Review.htm | title = Steve Harris \u2013 ''British Lion'' Review | accessdate = 6 October 2012 | last = Bowar | first = Chad | publisher = [[About.com]]}}</ref>\n| rev2 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev2Score = {{Rating|2.5|5}}<ref name= \"AM\">{{Allmusic|class=album|id=r2568550|first=James Christopher|last=Monger|title=Steve Harris \u2013 ''British Lion''|accessdate=6 October 2012}}</ref>\n| rev3 = [[Artistdirect]]\n| rev3Score = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref name=\"artistdirect\">{{cite web|title=Steve Harris ''British Lion'' Album Review \u2013 5 out of 5 stars|url=http://www.artistdirect.com/entertainment-news/article/steve-harris-british-lion-album-review-5-out-of-5-stars/10254241|publisher=[[Artistdirect]]|accessdate=2 April 2013|author=Rick Florino|date=2 October 2012}}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''[[Classic Rock (magazine)|Classic Rock]]''\n| rev4Score = 7/10<ref name=\"CR review\">{{cite journal | title = Steve Harris: ''British Lion'' | journal = [[Classic Rock (magazine)|Classic Rock]] | date = 1 October 2012 | first = Jon | last = Hotten | issue = 176 | pages = 96 | url = http://www.steveharrisbritishlion.com/reviews/crock.jpg | accessdate = 15 September 2012 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120919185549/http://steveharrisbritishlion.com/reviews/crock.jpg# | archive-date = 19 September 2012 | url-status = dead | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n| rev5 = [[Drowned in Sound]]\n| rev5Score = 3/10<ref name=\"drowned in sound\">{{cite web | url = http://drownedinsound.com/releases/17242/reviews/4145501?ticker | title = Steve Harris: ''British Lion'' | accessdate = 18 September 2012 | first = Ryan | last = Drever | publisher = [[Drowned in Sound]] | date = 18 September 2012}}</ref>\n| rev6 = ''[[Kerrang!]]''\n| rev6Score = {{rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"Kerrang!\">{{cite journal | title = Steve Harris: ''British Lion'' | journal = [[Kerrang!]] | date = 5 September 2012 | first = Nick | last = Ruskell | issue = 1431 | pages = 52 | url = http://www.steveharrisbritishlion.com/reviews/Kerrang.jpg | accessdate = 8 September 2012 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120919185739/http://steveharrisbritishlion.com/reviews/Kerrang.jpg# | archive-date = 19 September 2012 | url-status = dead | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n| rev7 = ''[[Metal Hammer]]''\n| rev7Score = 8/10<ref name=\"MHreview\">{{cite journal | title = Steve Harris: ''British Lion'' | journal = [[Metal Hammer]] | date = 1 October 2012 | first = Dom | last = Lawson | issue = 236 | url = http://www.steveharrisbritishlion.com/reviews/hammer_review.jpg | accessdate = 15 September 2012 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120919185637/http://steveharrisbritishlion.com/reviews/hammer_review.jpg# | archive-date = 19 September 2012 | url-status = dead | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n| rev8 = [[PopMatters]]\n| rev8Score = 5/10<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Ezell|first=Brice|title=Steve Harris: ''British Lion''|url=http://www.popmatters.com/pm/review/164520-steve-harris-british-lion/|magazine=[[PopMatters]]|accessdate=12 November 2012|date=12 November 2012}}</ref>\n| rev9 = ''[[Record Collector]]''\n| rev9Score = {{rating|3|5}}<ref name=\"Record Collector\">{{cite journal | title = Steve Harris \u2013 ''British Lion'' | journal = [[Record Collector]] | date = 1 October 2012 | first = Dayal | last = Patterson | issue = 406 | url = http://recordcollectormag.com/reviews/british-lion | accessdate = 24 September 2012}}</ref>\n| rev10 = ''[[Revolver (magazine)|Revolver]]''\n| rev10Score = 3/5<ref name=\"Revolver\">{{cite magazine | url = http://www.revolvermag.com/reviews/review-steve-harris-british-lion.html | title = Review: Steve Harris \u2013 ''British Lion'' | accessdate = 25 September 2012 | last = Grow | first = Kory | date = 25 September 2012 | magazine = [[Revolver (magazine)|Revolver]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120927032453/http://www.revolvermag.com/reviews/review-steve-harris-british-lion.html | archive-date = 27 September 2012 | url-status = dead }}</ref>\n}}\nAs of August 2013, ''British Lion'' holds a score of 56 at the aggregate review site [[Metacritic]], indicating \"mixed or average reviews\".<ref name=\"meta\"/> ''[[Record Collector]]'' awarded the album 3/5 and stated that \"though it's not entirely a chore to listen to, it is probably not memorable enough to appeal far outside of that circle [of Iron Maiden fans]\".<ref name=\"Record Collector\"/> ''[[Revolver (magazine)|Revolver]]'' also gave it a score of 3/5, although they praised the \"cohesive\" song-writing and referred to Taylor as \"a compelling hard-rock singer\".<ref name=\"Revolver\"/> [[AllMusic]] gave it a score of 2.5/5, deeming it \"a serviceable slab of unpretentious yet utterly forgettable '80s retro-metal that adheres to every clich\u00e9 in the book\".<ref name= \"AM\"/> Although they called it \"a solid \u201870s style hard rock effort\", [[About.com]] criticised some songs for being \"nothing but filler.\"<ref name=\"About.com\"/>\n\n''[[Kerrang!]]'' deemed it \"a brilliant album\", describing it as \"the sound of an incredibly talented songwriter stepping outside of what he'd normally do and indulging himself in something a bit different with a group of excellent musicians.\"<ref name=\"Kerrang!\"/> ''[[Metal Hammer]]'' were also very positive towards the release, praising the \"infectious re-imaginings of the [[UFO (band)|UFO]] and [[Thin Lizzy]] albums that inspired their creator as a kid,\" concluding that \"This is a big hearted and ferocious triumph.\"<ref name=\"MHreview\"/> Although they criticised the album's lyrics, ''[[Classic Rock (magazine)|Classic Rock]]'' complimented vocalist Richard Taylor and guitarist Graham Leslie, concluding that \"''British Lion'' is an album that is both exactly what you'd expect, and far better than that.\"<ref name=\"CR review\"/> [[Artistdirect]] awarded it full marks, stating that \"As far as songwriters go, [Harris is] on the level with [[Jimmy Page]] and [[Tony Iommi]], and his new album, ''British Lion'', proves that tenfold\".<ref name=\"artistdirect\"/>\n\n==Track listing==\nAll songs are written by [[Steve Harris (musician)|Steve Harris]], Richard Taylor, David Hawkins unless otherwise noted.\n{{tracklist\n| title1   = This Is My God\n| writer1   = \n| length1  = 4:57\n| title2   = Lost Worlds\n| writer2   =\n| length2  = 4:58\n| title3   = Karma Killer\n| writer3   = \n| length3  = 5:29\n| title4   = Us Against the World\n| writer4   = \n| length4  = 4:12\n| title5   = The Chosen Ones\n| writer5   = Harris, Taylor\n| length5  = 6:27\n| title6   = A World Without Heaven\n| writer6   = Barry Fitzgibbon, Harris, Grahame Leslie, Gary Liederman, Ian Roberts, Taylor\n| length6  = 7:02\n| title7   = Judas\n| writer7   = \n| length7  = 4:58\n| title8   = Eyes of the Young\n| writer8   = Harris, Leslie, Roberts, Taylor\n| length8  = 5:25\n| title9   = These Are the Hands\n| writer9   = \n| length9  = 4:28\n| title10  = The Lesson\n| writer10  = \n| length10 = 4:15\n| total_length  = 52:11\n}}\n\n==Personnel==\n*[[Steve Harris (musician)|Steve Harris]] \u2013 bass guitar, production\n*Richard Taylor \u2013 lead vocals, production\n*David Hawkins \u2013 guitars, keyboards (all tracks except 5, 6 and 8), production, recording\n*Grahame Leslie \u2013 guitars (tracks 5, 6 and 8)\n*Simon Dawson \u2013 drums (tracks 2, 4 and 9)\n\n===Additional personnel===\n*Barry Fitzgibbon \u2013 guitars (tracks 5, 6 and 8)\n*Ian Roberts \u2013 drums (tracks 5, 6 and 8)\n*Richard Cook \u2013 drums (tracks 1, 3 and 7)\n*[[Kevin Shirley]] \u2013 [[Audio mixing (recorded music)|mixing]]\n*Ade Emsley \u2013 [[Audio mastering|mastering]]\n\n==Chart performance==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"