ic Industry|Italian Albums Chart]]<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.fimi.it/classifiche_result_artisti.php?anno=%202012&mese=10&id=427 | title = FIMI Artisti Classifica settimanale dal 24/09/2012 al 30/09/2012 | accessdate = 4 October 2012 | date = 30 September 2012 | publisher = [[Federation of the Italian Music Industry]] | language = Italian | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150518084438/http://www.fimi.it/classifiche_result_artisti.php?anno=%202012&mese=10&id=427# | archive-date = 18 May 2015 | url-status = dead | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 39\n|-\n|[[VG-lista|Norwegian Albums Chart]]<ref>{{cite web | url = http://norwegiancharts.com/weekchart.asp?cat=a&year=2012&date=201240 | title = VG Lista \u2013 Album Top 40, Week 40/2012 | accessdate = 6 October 2012 | publisher = Norwegiancharts.com|work=[[VG-lista]]}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 30\n|-\n|[[Productores de M\u00fasica de Espa\u00f1a|Spanish Albums Chart]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.promusicae.org/files/listassemanales/albumes/top%20100%20albumes%20%28publicar%29_w39.2012.pdf |title=Top 100 Albumes Semana 39: del 24.09.2012 al 30.09.2012 |accessdate=3 October 2012 |date=30 September 2012 |publisher=[[Productores de M\u00fasica de Espa\u00f1a]] |language=Spanish |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6B8vyeRF9?url=http://www.promusicae.org/files/listassemanales/albumes/top%20100%20albumes%20%28publicar%29_w39.2012.pdf |archivedate=3 October 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 63\n|-\n|[[Sverigetopplistan|Swedish Albums Chart]]<ref name=\"sweden\">{{cite web | url = http://swedishcharts.com/weekchart.asp?cat=a&year=2012&date=20121005 | title = Sverigetopplistan \u2013 Albums Top 60, 5 October 2012  | accessdate = 6 October 2012 | date = 5 October 2012 | publisher = [[Sverigetopplistan]] | language = Swedish}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 18\n|-\n|[[Swiss Music Charts|Swiss Albums Chart]]<ref>{{cite web | url = http://hitparade.ch/weekchart.asp?cat=a&date=20121007&year=2012 | title = Schweizer Hitparade \u2013 Alben Top 100: 07.10.2012 | accessdate = 3 October 2012 | date = 3 October 2012 | publisher = [[Swiss Music Charts]] | language = German}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 40\n|-\n|[[UK Albums Chart]]<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.officialcharts.com/archive-chart/_/3/2012-10-06/ | title = Top 40 Official UK Albums Archive 6 October 2012 | accessdate = 30 September 2012 | date = 30 September 2012 | publisher = [[Official Charts Company]]}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|39\n|-\n|[[UK Rock & Metal Singles and Albums Charts|UK Rock & Metal Chart]]<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.officialcharts.com/archive-chart/_/11/2012-10-06/ | title = Top 40 Rock & Metal Albums Archive 6 October 2012 | accessdate = 30 September 2012 | date = 30 September 2012 | publisher = [[Official Charts Company]]}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n|-\n|US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]]<ref>{{cite web | url = {{BillboardURLbyName|artist=steve harris|chart=all}} | title = Steve Harris ''Billboard'' Albums | accessdate = 23 February 2013 | work = [[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] }}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 138\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:2012 debut albums]]\n[[Category:EMI Records albums]]\n[[Category:Heavy metal albums by English artists]]\n", "name_user": "MichaelSharman", "label": "safe", "comment": "I have added the link to the Steve Harris British Lion Band Wikipedia page.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/British_Lion_(album)"}
{"title_page": "Gnomon (novel)", "text_new": "{{Infobox book\n| name          = ''Gnomon''\n| title_orig    = \n| translator    = \n| image         = \n| image_caption = \n| author        = Nick Harkaway\n| illustrator   = \n| cover_artist  = \n| country       = [[United Kingdom]]\n| language      = English\n| series        = \n| subject       = <!-- Subject is not relevant for fiction -->\n| genre         = [[Science fiction]]\n| published     = 2017\n| media_type    = Print\n| pages         = 704\n| isbn          = 978-1-473-53954-9\n| oclc          = \n| preceded_by   = \n| followed_by   = \n| wikisource    = \n}}\n'''''Gnomon''''' is a [[science fiction]] novel by [[Nick Harkaway]]. The book  deals with a state that exerts ubiquitous surveillance on its population. A detective investigates a murder through unconventional methods that leads to questions about her society's very nature.\n\n== Plot summary ==\n\nIn a near future [[United Kingdom]], now governed by a continuous [[direct democracy]] called the System, all of Britain is under [[Surveillance state|constant surveillance]]  by the nigh-omniscient [[Artificial intelligence|AI]] called \"The Witness.\" The Witness AI is purported to be completely impartial, doing nothing \"unless public safety requires it. [...] It cannot be [[Security hacker|hacked, cracked,]] disabled or distorted. It [[Surveillance|sees]], it [[Self-awareness|understands]], and very occasionally it acts, but otherwise it is resolutely invisible.\" Mielikki Neith is an [[Inspector]] of the Witness Programme\u2014the \"prosecutorial [[Ombudsman|ombudsmen]] to the surveillance state, reviewing and considering any case that passes a given threshold of intervention.\"\n\nNeith  is tasked with investigating the death of 61 year old [[Luddite|luddite]] and \"writer of obscurantist [[Magic realism|magical realist]] novels\" Diana Hunter. Hunter has died mysteriously while in Witness [[Police custody in the United Kingdom|custody]] following her [[interrogation]], a process where Hunter's memories were forcibly extracted. Neith quickly finds that Hunter's memories are a seemingly impossible maze of other lives/narratives. In one narrative/memory thread, Neith sees the life of [[Greek]] [[investment banker]] Constantine Kyriakos in the early 21st century where he has a fateful encounter with a [[great white shark]]. In another, Neith sees the [[5th century]] [[Alchemy|alchemist]] lover of [[Augustine of Hippo]], Athenais Karthagonensis, as she endeavors to uncover the secrets of a chamber that could lead to the fabled [[Alcahest]] following the death of her son. In yet another, Neith sees [[Ethiopia|Ethiopian]] painter Berihun Bekele, who lives in [[London]] in the early 21st century and assists his granddaughter Annie with the development of a [[video game]], ''Witnessed,'' that bears striking resemblance to Neith's actual world.\n\n==Reception==\nIn [[The Independent|''The Independent'']], Darragh McManus gave a negative review,<ref>{{cite web |last1=McManus |first1=Darragh |title=Baffling utopian epic ladled with elegant nonsense |url=https://www.independent.ie/entertainment/books/book-reviews/baffling-utopian-epic-ladled-with-elegant-nonsense-36305841.html |website=The Independent |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> calling the book a \"baffling utopian epic ladled with elegant nonsense.\" While praising Harkaway for \"writing women extremely well\" (\"Hunter, Neith and Athenais are the book's most vivid creations and strongest elements\"), and saying \"there are a lot of things to enjoy in ''Gnomon'',\" she nevertheless felt it was \"hugely confusing.\"\n\n<blockquote>It's not the length, though the novel is much too long. It's not that Harkaway has a tendency to overwrite: both in labouring a point or observation before labouring it some more, and using arcane (and possibly non-existent) words where a normal, widely-known one was available. [...] My main problem is that ''Gnomon'' doesn't make a lick of sense. Or maybe it does, in the author's mind, but I'm afraid I was baffled, to the point of paralysed stupidity. I genuinely couldn't tell you, by the end, who did what and when, whether anything reported here actually occurred, whether any or all of these characters even exist.</blockquote>\n\nIn [[The Guardian|''The Guardian'']], Steven Poole also gave the book a relatively negative review.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Poole |first1=Steven |title=Gnomon by Nick Harkaway review \u2013 a future of total surveillance |url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2017/nov/16/gnomon-nick-harkaway-review-science-fiction-artifical-intelligence |website=The Guardian |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> \"''Gnomon'' [...] reads like the first draft of what might have been a tighter 400-page book rather than a rambling 700-pager. Progress is routinely halted by sketchy Wikipedia-style exposition-dumps about tidal flow or [[behavioural economics]], or a character asking herself a whole page or two of questions about what just happened, or vague disquisitions on the meaning of identity. Things are repeatedly explained, unnecessarily.\" Still, Poole also said, \"Such defects wouldn\u2019t be so annoying were it not obvious that Nick Harkaway can sometimes be a very good writer indeed. Readers who are prepared to mentally edit the book as they go along, as the author and editor have not, will encounter a host of highly enjoyable fragments and suggestive ideas.\"\n\nFor [[NPR]], Jason Sheehan gave a mixed review,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Sheehan |first1=Jason |title='Gnomon' Starts Simply \u2014 And Then It Goes Sideways |url=https://www.npr.org/2018/01/07/573582683/gnomon-starts-simply-and-then-it-goes-sideways |website=NPR |accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref> saying, \"it's a big book, a digressive book, and it contains so much that it sometimes feels (like Diana Hunter's house is supposed to feel) like a museum of curiosities trapped between two covers and shaken vigorously. You can't help but be hooked by a detail here, a tic of recursive language there, until suddenly, you know things about [[Isis]], ocean water or the [[Thames]] that you never thought would be interesting until Harkaway dangled them in front of you.\"\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n[https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/33852053-gnomon ''Gnomon'' on Goodreads]\n\n[[Category:2017 novels]]\n[[Category:British novels]]\n[[Category:Science fiction novels]]\n[[Category:English-language novels]]\n[[Category:Novels set in the United Kingdom]]\n{{sf-novel-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox book\n| name          = ''Gnomon''\n| title_orig    = \n| translator    = \n| image         = \n| image_caption = \n| author        = Nick Harkaway\n| illustrator   = \n| cover_artist  = \n| country       = [[United Kingdom]]\n| language      = English\n| series        = \n| subject       = <!-- Subject is not relevant for fiction -->\n| genre         = [[Science fiction]]\n| published     = 2017\n| media_type    = Print\n| pages         = 704\n| isbn          = 978-1-473-53954-9\n| oclc          = \n| preceded_by   = \n| followed_by   = \n| wikisource    = \n}}\n'''''Gnomon''''' is a [[science fiction]] novel by [[Nick Harkaway]]. The book  deals with a state that exerts ubiquitous surveillance on its population. A detective investigates a murder through unconventional methods that leads to questions about her society's very nature.\n\n== Plot summary ==\n\nIn a near future [[United Kingdom]], now governed by a continuous [[direct democracy]] called the System, all of Britain is under [[Surveillance state|constant surveillance]]  by the nigh-omniscient [[Artificial intelligence|AI]] called \"The Witness.\" The Witness AI is purported to be completely impartial, doing nothing \"unless public safety requires it. [...] It cannot be [[Security hacker|hacked, cracked,]] disabled or distorted. It [[Surveillance|sees]], it [[Self-awareness|understands]], and very occasionally it acts, but otherwise it is resolutely invisible.\" Mielikki Neith is an [[Inspector]] of the Witness Programme\u2014the \"prosecutorial [[Ombudsman|ombudsmen]] to the surveillance state, reviewing and considering any case that passes a given threshold of intervention.\"\n\nNeith  is tasked with investigating the death of [[Luddite|luddite]] Diana Hunter's death while in Witness [[Police custody in the United Kingdom|custody]] following her [[interrogation]] (a process where Hunter's memories were forcibly extracted). Neith quickly finds that Hunter's memories are a seemingly impossible maze of other lives/narratives. In one narrative/memory thread, Neith sees the life of [[Greek]] [[investment banker]] Constantine Kyriakos in the early 21st century where he has a fateful encounter with a [[great white shark]]. In another, Neith sees the [[5th century]] [[Alchemy|alchemist]] lover of [[Augustine of Hippo]], Athenais Karthagonensis, as she endeavors to uncover the secrets of a chamber that could lead to the fabled [[Alcahest]] following the death of her son. In yet another, Neith sees [[Ethiopia|Ethiopian]] painter Berihun Bekele, who lives in [[London]] in the early 21st century and assists his granddaughter Annie with the development of a [[video game]], ''Witnessed,'' that bears striking resemblance to Neith's actual world.\n\n==Reception==\nIn [[The Independent|''The Independent'']], Darragh McManus gave a negative review,<ref>{{cite web |last1=McManus |first1=Darragh |title=Baffling utopian epic ladled with elegant nonsense |url=https://www.independent.ie/entertainment/books/book-reviews/baffling-utopian-epic-ladled-with-elegant-nonsense-36305841.html |website=The Independent |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> calling the book a \"baffling utopian epic ladled with elegant nonsense.\" While praising Harkaway for \"writing women extremely well\" (\"Hunter, Neith and Athenais are the book's most vivid creations and strongest elements\"), and saying \"there are a lot of things to enjoy in ''Gnomon'',\" she nevertheless felt it was \"hugely confusing.\"\n\n<blockquote>It's not the length, though the novel is much too long. It's not that Harkaway has a tendency to overwrite: both in labouring a point or observation before labouring it some more, and using arcane (and possibly non-existent) words where a normal, widely-known one was available. [...] My main problem is that ''Gnomon'' doesn't make a lick of sense. Or maybe it does, in the author's mind, but I'm afraid I was baffled, to the point of paralysed stupidity. I genuinely couldn't tell you, by the end, who did what and when, whether anything reported here actually occurred, whether any or all of these characters even exist.</blockquote>\n\nIn [[The Guardian|''The Guardian'']], Steven Poole also gave the book a relatively negative review.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Poole |first1=Steven |title=Gnomon by Nick Harkaway review \u2013 a future of total surveillance |url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2017/nov/16/gnomon-nick-harkaway-review-science-fiction-artifical-intelligence |website=The Guardian |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref> \"''Gnomon'' [...] reads like the first draft of what might have been a tighter 400-page book rather than a rambling 700-pager. Progress is routinely halted by sketchy Wikipedia-style exposition-dumps about tidal flow or [[behavioural economics]], or a character asking herself a whole page or two of questions about what just happened, or vague disquisitions on the meaning of identity. Things are repeatedly explained, unnecessarily.\" Still, Poole also said, \"Such defects wouldn\u2019t be so annoying were it not obvious that Nick Harkaway can sometimes be a very good writer indeed. Readers who are prepared to mentally edit the book as they go along, as the author and editor have not, will encounter a host of highly enjoyable fragments and suggestive ideas.\"\n\nFor [[NPR]], Jason Sheehan gave a mixed review,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Sheehan |first1=Jason |title='Gnomon' Starts Simply \u2014 And Then It Goes Sideways |url=https://www.npr.org/2018/01/07/573582683/gnomon-starts-simply-and-then-it-goes-sideways |website=NPR |accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref> saying, \"it's a big book, a digressive book, and it contains so much that it sometimes feels (like Diana Hunter's house is supposed to feel) like a museum of curiosities trapped between two covers and shaken vigorously. You can't help but be hooked by a detail here, a tic of recursive language there, until suddenly, you know things about [[Isis]], ocean water or the [[Thames]] that you never thought would be interesting until Harkaway dangled them in front of you.\"\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n[https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/33852053-gnomon ''Gnomon'' on Goodreads]\n\n[[Category:2017 novels]]\n[[Category:British novels]]\n[[Category:Science fiction novels]]\n[[Category:English-language novels]]\n[[Category:Novels set in the United Kingdom]]\n{{sf-novel-stub}}\n", "name_user": "RobertM525", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePlot summary", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gnomon_(novel)"}
{"title_page": "Aurel Aldea", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n|birth_date=18 March 1887\n|birth_place=[[Slatina, Romania|Slatina]], [[Olt County]], [[Kingdom of Romania]]\n|death_date={{D-da|17 October 1949|18 March 1887}}\n|death_place=[[Aiud Prison]], [[Aiud]], [[Alba County]], [[Romania]]\n|occupation=General<br> Interior Minister<br> Anti-communist resistance leader\n}}\n'''Aurel Aldea''' (18 March 1887 \u2013 17 October 1949) was a [[Romania]]n general, [[Ministry of Internal Affairs (Romania)|Interior Minister]], and [[Romanian anti-communist resistance movement|anti-communist resistance]] leader.\n\n==Biography ==\n\nAurel Aldea was born in [[Slatina, Romania|Slatina]], [[Olt County]] on 28 March 1887. He graduated from the Artillery and Engineering Military School of [[Ia\u0219i]], after which he was sent to [[Germany]] to the Preparatory School of Military Officers of [[Hanover]] (1907\u20131912) and to the Military Technical Academy of [[Charlottenburg]], where he had his internship at the 23rd Artillery Regiment in [[Koblenz]].<ref name=Alesandru>Du\u021bu Alesandru and Dobre Florica: ''Drama generalilor rom\u00e2ni'', p. 22</ref> \n\nIn 1912 Aldea was recalled to Romania to participate in the [[Second Balkan War]], and in 1913 he graduated from the [[Carol I National Defence University|Higher War School]]. He served in [[World War I]] as a battery commander, and participated in the battles from [[Dobruja|Dobrogea]] and [[Bucharest]].\n\nIn the [[interwar period]] Aldea worked within the General Staff of the [[Romanian Armed Forces]] in the Transport Division and Historic Service, Head of Staff of the 11th Infantry Division and [[First Army (Romania)|1st Army Corps]], then commander of the 23rd Artillery Regiment. Between 1935 and 1938  he was the commander of the Artillery Brigade, after which he was appointed Secretary General of the Ministry of Army Endowment and Commander of the 11th Infantry Division (autumn 1938) and [[4th Infantry Division (Romania)|4th Infantry Division]] (April 1939).<ref name=Alesandru/>\n\nAfter [[King Michael's Coup]], Aldea served as Interior Minister in the [[Constantin S\u0103n\u0103tescu]] government from August 23 to November 4, 1944.<ref name=\"gen\">{{cite web|url=http://www.generals.dk/general/Aldea/Aurel/Romania.html|title=Aldea, Aurel|website=generals.dk|access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\nHe was arrested on May 27, 1946 and was condemned to life in prison for his resistance efforts on November 18, 1946. He died in [[Aiud Prison]] on October 17, 1949.<ref name=\"gen\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.historica-cluj.ro/anuare/AnuarHistorica2010/09.pdf |title=Mor\u021bii Penitenciarului Aiud 1945-1965|page= 19|first1=Virgiliu |last1=\u021a\u00e2r\u0103u|first2=Ioan|last2= Ciupea|language=Romanian|access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{cite web|url=https://www.cotidianul.ro/interesant-o-alta-istorie-ascunsa-de-marii-istorici-ai-institutului-de-istorie-nationala/|title=Interesant, o alt\u0103 istorie ascuns\u0103 de marii istorici ai Institutului de Istorie Na\u021bional\u0103|newspaper=[[Cotidianul]]|date=June 3, 2012|access-date=April 15, 2020}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Aldea, Aurel}}\n[[Category:1887 births]]\n[[Category:1949 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Slatina, Romania]]\n[[Category:Inmates of Aiud prison]]\n[[Category:Prisoners who died in Romanian detention]]\n[[Category:Prisoners sentenced to life imprisonment by Romania]]\n[[Category:Romanian dissidents]]\n[[Category:Romanian Land Forces generals]]\n[[Category:Romanian military personnel of the Second Balkan War]]\n[[Category:Romanian military personnel of World War I]]\n[[Category:Romanian people of World War II]]\n[[Category:Romanian people who died in prison custody]]\n[[Category:Romanian Ministers of Interior]]\n[[Category:Carol I National Defence University alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n|birth_date=18 March 1887\n|birth_place=[[Slatina, Romania|Slatina]], [[Olt County]], [[Kingdom of Romania]]\n|death_date={{D-da|17 October 1949|18 March 1887}}\n|death_place=[[Aiud Prison]], [[Aiud]], [[Alba County]], [[Romania]]\n|occupation=General<br> Interior Minister<br> Anti-communist resistance leader\n}}\n'''Aurel Aldea''' (18 March 1887 \u2013 17 October 1949) was a [[Romania]]n general, [[Ministry of Internal Affairs (Romania)|Interior Minister]], and [[Romanian anti-communist resistance movement|anti-communist resistance]] leader.\n\n==Biography ==\n\nAurel Aldea was born in [[Slatina, Romania|Slatina]], [[Olt County]] on 28 March 1887. He graduated from the Artillery and Engineering Military School of [[Ia\u0219i]], after which he was sent to [[Germany]] to the Preparatory School of Military Officers of [[Hanover]] (1907\u20131912) and to the Military Technical Academy of [[Charlottenburg]], where he had his internship at the 23rd Artillery Regiment in [[Koblenz]].<ref name=Alesandru>Du\u021bu Alesandru and Dobre Florica: ''Drama generalilor rom\u00e2ni'', p. 22</ref> \n\nIn 1912 Aldea was recalled to Romania to participate in the [[Second Balkan War]], and in 1913 he graduated from the [[Carol I National Defence University|Higher War School]]. He served in [[World War I]] as a battery commander, and participated in the battles from [[Dobruja|Dobrogea]] and [[Bucharest]].\n\nIn the [[interwar period]] Aldea worked within the General Staff of the [[Romanian Armed Forces]] in the Transport Division and Historic Service, Head of Staff of the 11th Infantry Division and [[First Army (Romania)|1st Army Corps]], then commander of the 23rd Artillery Regiment. Between 1935 and 1938  he was the commander of the Artillery Brigade, after which he was appointed Secretary General of the Ministry of Army Endowment and Commander of the 11th Infantry Division (autumn 1938) and [[4th Infantry Division (Romania)|4th Infantry Division]] (April 1939).<ref name=Alesandru/>\n\nAfter [[King Michael's Coup]], Aldea served as Interior Minister in the [[Constantin S\u0103n\u0103tescu]] government from August 23 to November 4, 1944.<ref name=\"gen\">{{cite web|url=http://www.generals.dk/general/Aldea/Aurel/Romania.html|title=Aldea, Aurel|website=generals.dk|access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\nHe was arrested on May 27, 1946 and was condemned to life in prison for his resistance efforts on November 18, 1946. He died in [[Aiud Prison]] on October 17, 1949.<ref name=\"gen\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.historica-cluj.ro/anuare/AnuarHistorica2010/09.pdf |title=Mor\u021bii Penitenciarului Aiud 1945-1965|page= 19|first1=Virgiliu |last1=\u021a\u00e2r\u0103u|first2=Ioan|last2= Ciupea|language=Romanian|access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.generals.dk/general/Aldea/Aurel/Romania.html|title= Aldea Biographical Information}}\n*{{cite web|url=https://www.cotidianul.ro/interesant-o-alta-istorie-ascunsa-de-marii-istorici-ai-institutului-de-istorie-nationala/|title=Interesant, o alt\u0103 istorie ascuns\u0103 de marii istorici ai Institutului de Istorie Na\u021bional\u0103|newspaper=[[Cotidianul]]|date=June 3, 2012|access-date=April 15, 2020}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Aldea, Aurel}}\n[[Category:1887 births]]\n[[Category:1949 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Slatina, Romania]]\n[[Category:Inmates of Aiud prison]]\n[[Category:Prisoners who died in Romanian detention]]\n[[Category:Prisoners sentenced to life imprisonment by Romania]]\n[[Category:Romanian dissidents]]\n[[Category:Romanian Land Forces generals]]\n[[Category:Romanian military personnel of the Second Balkan War]]\n[[Category:Romanian military personnel of World War I]]\n[[Category:Romanian people of World War II]]\n[[Category:Romanian people who died in prison custody]]\n[[Category:Romanian Ministers of Interior]]\n[[Category:Carol I National Defence University alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Turgidson", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:delete duplicate ref", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aurel_Aldea"}
{"title_page": "A51 road", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2013}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2013}}\n{{Infobox road\n|country=GBR\n|type=A\n|route=51\n|image=  A51 road, Boughton.JPG     \n|image_notes=  The A51 in [[Boughton, Cheshire|Boughton]] looking towards [[Chester]]\n|map=[[File:A51 road map.png|300px]]\n|map_custom=yes\n|length_mi= 79\n|direction_a= Northwest\n|terminus_a = [[Chester]]<br><small>{{coord|52.5586|-1.6808|type:landmark_region:GB|display=inline|name=A51, northern terminus}}<small>\n|direction_b= Southeast\n|terminus_b = [[Kingsbury, Warwickshire|Kingsbury]]<br><small>{{coord|53.1921|-2.8821|type:landmark_region:GB|display=inline|name=A51, southern terminus}}<small>\n|established= 1922\n|junction   = {{collapsible list\n| title = [[Cheshire]]\n|[[File:UK road A5268.PNG|1000x20px]]<br>[[A5268 road]]\n|[[File:UK road A5115.PNG|1000x20px]]<br>[[A5115 road]]\n|[[File:UK road A41.svg|1000x20px]]<br>[[A41 road]]\n|[[File:UK road A55.svg|1000x20px]]<br>[[A55 road]]\n|[[File:UK road A54.svg|1000x20px]]<br>[[A54 road]]\n|[[File:UK road A49.svg|1000x20px]]<br>[[A49 road]]\n|[[File:UK road A534.PNG|1000x20px]]<br>[[A534 road]]\n|[[File:UK road A530.PNG|1000x20px]]<br>[[A530 road]]\n|[[File:UK road A500.PNG|1000x20px]]<br>[[A500 road]]\n}}\n{{collapsible list\n| title = [[Shropshire]]\n|[[File:UK road A525.svg|1000x20px]]<br>[[A525 road]]\n}}\n{{collapsible list\n| title = [[Staffordshire]]\n|[[File:UK road A53.svg|1000x20px]]<br>[[A53 road]]\n|[[File:UK road A34.svg|1000x20px]]<br>[[A34 road]]\n|[[File:UK road A518.svg|1000x20px]]<br>[[A518 road]]\n|[[File:UK road A513.svg|1000x20px]]<br>[[A513 road]]\n|[[File:UK road A460.svg|1000x20px]]<br>[[A460 road]]\n|[[File:UK road A515.svg|1000x20px]]<br>[[A515 road]]\n|[[File:UK road A5192.PNG|1000x20px]]<br>[[A5192 road]]\n|[[File:UK road A5206.PNG|1000x20px]]<br>[[A5206 road]]\n|[[File:UK road A453.PNG|1000x20px]]<br>[[A453 road]]\n|[[File:UK road A513.svg|1000x20px]]<br>[[A513 road]]\n}}\n|maint=<br>[[Cheshire East Council]]<br>[[Cheshire West and Chester Council]]<br>[[Shropshire Council]]<br>[[Staffordshire County Council]]<br>[[Warwickshire County Council]]\n|counties=[[Cheshire]], [[Shropshire]], [[Staffordshire]], [[Warwickshire]]\n|destinations=[[Chester]]<br>[[Nantwich]]<br>[[Stone, Staffordshire|Stone]]<br>[[Rugeley]]<br>[[Lichfield]]<br>[[Tamworth, Staffordshire|Tamworth]]\n|previous_type = A\n|previous_route = 50\n|next_type = A\n|next_route = 52\n}}\n\nThe '''A51''' is a road in [[England]] running from [[Chester]] to [[Kingsbury, Warwickshire|Kingsbury]], Warwickshire. Much like its [[Samsung Galaxy A51|mobile counterpart]], the A51 road is famously [[Waterproofing|waterproof]].\n\nIt takes on the following route:\n*[[Chester]]\n*[[Vicars Cross]]\n*[[Littleton, Cheshire|Littleton]]\n*[[Tarvin]]\n*[[Duddon]]\n*[[Clotton]]\n*[[Tarporley]] (merges briefly with [[A49 road|A49]])\n*[[Nantwich]]\n*[[Woore]]\n*[[Stone, Staffordshire|Stone]] (merges briefly with [[A34 road (England)|A34]])\n*[[Sandon, Staffordshire|Sandon]]\n*[[Weston, Staffordshire|Weston]]\n*[[Great Haywood]]\n*[[Little Haywood]]\n*[[Rugeley]] (bypass opened 2007 [https://web.archive.org/web/20081121000416/http://www.rugeleybypass.co.uk/])\n*[[Lichfield]]\n*[[Tamworth, Staffordshire|Tamworth]]\n*[[Kingsbury, Warwickshire|Kingsbury]]\n\nThe A51 is used by some long-distance traffic as an alternative to the [[M6 motorway]], which is prone to congestion through [[Birmingham]]. The nearby [[M6 Toll]] motorway now serves a similar function. Previously continued to Coventry via route of B4098.\n\n{{GeoGroupTemplate}}\n{{GB A road zone 5}}\n\n{{coord|52.9421|-2.2707|dim:50000_region:GB|display=title|name=A51 road}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:5-0051}}\n[[Category:Roads in England]]\n[[Category:Roads in Cheshire]]\n[[Category:Transport in Staffordshire]]\n[[Category:Roads in Warwickshire]]\n\n\n{{England-road-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2013}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2013}}\n{{Infobox road\n|country=GBR\n|type=A\n|route=51\n|image=  A51 road, Boughton.JPG     \n|image_notes=  The A51 in [[Boughton, Cheshire|Boughton]] looking towards [[Chester]]\n|map=[[File:A51 road map.png|300px]]\n|map_custom=yes\n|length_mi= 79\n|direction_a= Northwest\n|terminus_a = [[Chester]]<br><small>{{coord|52.5586|-1.6808|type:landmark_region:GB|display=inline|name=A51, northern terminus}}<small>\n|direction_b= Southeast\n|terminus_b = [[Kingsbury, Warwickshire|Kingsbury]]<br><small>{{coord|53.1921|-2.8821|type:landmark_region:GB|display=inline|name=A51, southern terminus}}<small>\n|established= 1922\n|junction   = {{collapsible list\n| title = [[Cheshire]]\n|[[File:UK road A5268.PNG|1000x20px]]<br>[[A5268 road]]\n|[[File:UK road A5115.PNG|1000x20px]]<br>[[A5115 road]]\n|[[File:UK road A41.svg|1000x20px]]<br>[[A41 road]]\n|[[File:UK road A55.svg|1000x20px]]<br>[[A55 road]]\n|[[File:UK road A54.svg|1000x20px]]<br>[[A54 road]]\n|[[File:UK road A49.svg|1000x20px]]<br>[[A49 road]]\n|[[File:UK road A534.PNG|1000x20px]]<br>[[A534 road]]\n|[[File:UK road A530.PNG|1000x20px]]<br>[[A530 road]]\n|[[File:UK road A500.PNG|1000x20px]]<br>[[A500 road]]\n}}\n{{collapsible list\n| title = [[Shropshire]]\n|[[File:UK road A525.PNG|1000x20px]]<br>[[A525 road]]\n}}\n{{collapsible list\n| title = [[Staffordshire]]\n|[[File:UK road A53.svg|1000x20px]]<br>[[A53 road]]\n|[[File:UK road A34.svg|1000x20px]]<br>[[A34 road]]\n|[[File:UK road A518.svg|1000x20px]]<br>[[A518 road]]\n|[[File:UK road A513.svg|1000x20px]]<br>[[A513 road]]\n|[[File:UK road A460.svg|1000x20px]]<br>[[A460 road]]\n|[[File:UK road A515.svg|1000x20px]]<br>[[A515 road]]\n|[[File:UK road A5192.PNG|1000x20px]]<br>[[A5192 road]]\n|[[File:UK road A5206.PNG|1000x20px]]<br>[[A5206 road]]\n|[[File:UK road A453.PNG|1000x20px]]<br>[[A453 road]]\n|[[File:UK road A513.svg|1000x20px]]<br>[[A513 road]]\n}}\n|maint=<br>[[Cheshire East Council]]<br>[[Cheshire West and Chester Council]]<br>[[Shropshire Council]]<br>[[Staffordshire County Council]]<br>[[Warwickshire County Council]]\n|counties=[[Cheshire]], [[Shropshire]], [[Staffordshire]], [[Warwickshire]]\n|destinations=[[Chester]]<br>[[Nantwich]]<br>[[Stone, Staffordshire|Stone]]<br>[[Rugeley]]<br>[[Lichfield]]<br>[[Tamworth, Staffordshire|Tamworth]]\n|previous_type = A\n|previous_route = 50\n|next_type = A\n|next_route = 52\n}}\n\nThe '''A51''' is a road in [[England]] running from [[Chester]] to [[Kingsbury, Warwickshire|Kingsbury]], Warwickshire. Much like its [[Samsung Galaxy A51|mobile counterpart]], the A51 road is famously [[Waterproofing|waterproof]].\n\nIt takes on the following route:\n*[[Chester]]\n*[[Vicars Cross]]\n*[[Littleton, Cheshire|Littleton]]\n*[[Tarvin]]\n*[[Duddon]]\n*[[Clotton]]\n*[[Tarporley]] (merges briefly with [[A49 road|A49]])\n*[[Nantwich]]\n*[[Woore]]\n*[[Stone, Staffordshire|Stone]] (merges briefly with [[A34 road (England)|A34]])\n*[[Sandon, Staffordshire|Sandon]]\n*[[Weston, Staffordshire|Weston]]\n*[[Great Haywood]]\n*[[Little Haywood]]\n*[[Rugeley]] (bypass opened 2007 [https://web.archive.org/web/20081121000416/http://www.rugeleybypass.co.uk/])\n*[[Lichfield]]\n*[[Tamworth, Staffordshire|Tamworth]]\n*[[Kingsbury, Warwickshire|Kingsbury]]\n\nThe A51 is used by some long-distance traffic as an alternative to the [[M6 motorway]], which is prone to congestion through [[Birmingham]]. The nearby [[M6 Toll]] motorway now serves a similar function. Previously continued to Coventry via route of B4098.\n\n{{GeoGroupTemplate}}\n{{GB A road zone 5}}\n\n{{coord|52.9421|-2.2707|dim:50000_region:GB|display=title|name=A51 road}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:5-0051}}\n[[Category:Roads in England]]\n[[Category:Roads in Cheshire]]\n[[Category:Transport in Staffordshire]]\n[[Category:Roads in Warwickshire]]\n\n\n{{England-road-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Rschen7754", "label": "safe", "comment": "(GR)File:UK road A525.PNG\u2192File:UK road A525.svgsvg", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/A51_road"}
{"title_page": "Surgana State", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2017}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=May 2017}}\n{{Infobox former subdivision\n|native_name = \u0938\u0941\u0930\u0917\u093e\u0923\u093e \n|conventional_long_name =Surgana State \n|common_name =Surgana\n|nation = [[British India]]\n|subdivision = [[Princely State]]\n|era = \n|year_start = Late 18th century\n|date_start = \n|event_start= \n|year_end = 1948\n|date_end = \n|event_end= [[Independence of India]]\n|event1 = \n|date_event1 = \n|p1         =\n|s1         = India\n|flag_p1    = \n|flag_s1    = Flag of India.svg\n|image_flag = Surgana State flag.png\n|image_coat = COA surgana.jpg\n|image_map  = Nasik Agency Surgana State during British India.svg\n|image_map_caption = Surgana State in Nasik Agency during British India\n|stat_area1 = 932.4\n|stat_year1 = 1901\n|stat_pop1  =  11,532 \n|stat_area2 =\n|stat_year2 = 1921\n|stat_pop2  =  14,912\n|footnotes  =\n|today      = [[Maharashtra]], India\n|demonym=[[Koli People|Kolis]]|capital=[[Surgana]]|house1=[[Pawar]]}}\n'''Surgana State''' was a [[princely state]] of the [[Bombay Presidency]] during the era of the [[British Raj]].<ref>{{cite EB1911 |wstitle=Bombay Presidency |volume=4 |page=186}}</ref> It was the only state belonging to the Nasik Agency. Its capital was [[Surgana]] in [[Nashik District]] of present-day [[Maharashtra]].\n \nSurgana State's last ruler signed the accession to join the [[Indian Union]] in March 1948.\n\n== History ==\nSurgana State was founded towards the end of the 18th century. The territory of the state is [[mountainous]]. The chiefs of Surgana were [[Maratha]] Kshatriya's from Malwa and the ancestors trace their genealogy to Parmar from [[Mount Abu]] and Rajasthan. They  prevented the [[Bhils]] and [[Kol people|Kol]] of [[Dang District, India|the Dangs]] from raiding [[Hatgadh Fort]] and the [[Western Ghats|ghats]]. They also provided military services to neighbouring 14 chiefs. They were titled as [[Deshmukh]] \"Desh\" means \"country\" and \"Mukh\" means \"mouth\" Spoke person of his country, of the [[Hatgadh Fort|Hatgadh]] division of Nasik which included the town of Surgana and other villages. They refused to pay tribute to the [[Maratha Empire|Maratha]]s and [[Mughal Empire|Mughal]]s so they were marked as rebel land (Bandi Mulk). Due to their strategic position between [[Surat]] and [[Deccan Plateau|Deccan]], Marathas made peace with them. In 1818, they attacked a British police party passing through their state. The British retaliated and captured the chief Malhar Rao and hanged him in 1819. So Surgana State became a [[British protectorate]] in 1818.<ref>[http://www.worldstatesmen.org/India_princes_K-W.html Princely States of India]</ref> The British made Bhikaji Rao as the new chief as he helped them against the Marathas. Bhikaji Rao was murdered in the riot caused by the mother of Malharrao and her brother-in-law, Pilaji. Pilaji was captured and executed by the British. The descendants of Malharrao were allowed the share in revenues of the state in 1846 and were granted an allowance grant in 1877. The chief of the state had powers to elect a Representative Member of the Chambers of Princes from 1921 to 1947. In March 1948, the last chief Dhairyashil Rao signed the Gujarat States Merger Agreement and ceded the state to Union of India.\n\nLater Dhairyashil Rao also served as the Member of the [[Rajya Sabha]] in 1952\u20131968 and 1972\u20131978.\n\nThe Princely State was bordered on the south by Peinth in Nasik, and in the west by the [[Bansda State|Bansda]] and [[Dharampur State]]s.\n\n===Rulers===\nThe rulers of the state bore the title '[[Deshmukh]]'. Surgana State's rulers belonged to the Hindu [[Pawar]] dynasty of [[Kshatriya]] [[Koli People|Kolis]].<ref>[http://indpaedia.com/ind/index.php/Surgana/view/surgana  Koli Provinces of India Surgana (Princely State)]</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/dli.csl.3300|page=[https://archive.org/details/dli.csl.3300/page/n517 612]|title=Gazetteer of the Bombay Presidency: Kh\u00e1ndesh|date=1880|publisher=Government Central Press|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Lethbridge|first=Sir Roper|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=7iOsNUZ2MXgC&pg=PA521&dq=Surgana+Golden+Boom&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj6pePZqbfoAhUX73MBHbVqA5wQ6AEIGzAA#v=onepage&q=Surgana%20Golden%20Boom&f=false|title=The Golden Book of India: A Genealogical and Biographical Dictionary of the Ruling Princes, Chiefs, Nobles, and Other Personages, Titled Or Decorated of the Indian Empire|date=2005|publisher=Aakar Books|isbn=978-81-87879-54-1|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gazetteers.maharashtra.gov.in/cultural.maharashtra.gov.in/english/gazetteer/Khandesh%20District/state_surgana.html#1|title=Maharashtra Gazetteer|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=KARR|first=G. B. SETON|url=http://archive.org/details/dli.bengal.10689.13419|title=ROUGH NOTES|date=1855|publisher=BOMBAY EDUCATION SOCIETY\u2019S PRESS, BOMBAY}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=vw4_AAAAYAAJ&pg=PA169&dq=Deshmooks+Kolee&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjp0vvLv7foAhUTjeYKHW2GCCMQ6AEIGzAA#v=onepage&q=Deshmooks%20Kolee&f=false|title=Selections from the Records of the Bombay Government|date=1856|publisher=Government at the Bombay Education Society's Press|language=en}}</ref>\n\n====Deshmukhs====\n*bf.1800 \u2013 1818             .....\n*1818 \u2013 1819                Malhar Rao                         (d. 1819) \n*1819 \u2013 1820                Bhikaji Rao \n*1820 \u2013 1854                Jashwant Rao I Bhikaji Rao \n*1854 \u2013 1867                Muvar Rao \n*1867 \u2013  2 Jun 1898         Shankar Rao Ravi Rao               (b. 1849 \u2013 d. ....) \n*1898 \u2013 22 Jun 1930         Pratap Rao Shankar Rao             (b. 18 Aug 1880 \u2013 d. 1930) \n*1930 \u2013 1936                Jashwant Rao II Pratap Rao         (b. 1902 \u2013 d. ....)\n*Apr 1936 \u2013 15 Aug 1947 (1948 \u2013 2003 titular)     Dhairyashil Rao Jashwant Rao     (b. 22 Nov 1922 \u2013 d. 23 Nov 2003)\n*2003 \u2013 present (titular)     Nitranjan Dhairyashil Rao\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Rajput dynasties and states]]\n*[[Political integration of India]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://members.iinet.net.au/~royalty/ips/s/surgana.html Surgana (Princely State)]\n{{Coord|20.57|N|73.62|E|region:IN-GU_type:city_source:kolossus-cawiki|display=title}}\n{{Princely states of the Baroda and Gujarat States Agency}}\n\n[[Category:Nashik district]]\n[[Category:Princely states of Maharashtra]]\n[[Category:Rajputs]]\n[[Category:Koli princely states]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2017}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=May 2017}}\n{{Infobox former subdivision\n|native_name = \u0938\u0941\u0930\u0917\u093e\u0923\u093e \n|conventional_long_name =Surgana State \n|common_name =Surgana\n|nation = [[British India]]\n|subdivision = [[Princely State]]\n|era = \n|year_start = Late 18th century\n|date_start = \n|event_start= \n|year_end = 1948\n|date_end = \n|event_end= [[Independence of India]]\n|event1 = \n|date_event1 = \n|p1         =\n|s1         = India\n|flag_p1    = \n|flag_s1    = Flag of India.svg\n|image_flag = Surgana State flag.png\n|image_coat = COA surgana.jpg\n|image_map  = Nasik Agency Surgana State during British India.svg\n|image_map_caption = Surgana State in Nasik Agency during British India\n|stat_area1 = 932.4\n|stat_year1 = 1901\n|stat_pop1  =  11,532 \n|stat_area2 =\n|stat_year2 = 1921\n|stat_pop2  =  14,912\n|footnotes  =\n|today      = [[Maharashtra]], India\n|demonym=[[Koli People|Kolis]]|capital=[[Surgana]]|house1=[[Pawar]]}}\n'''Surgana State''' was a [[princely state]] of the [[Bombay Presidency]] during the era of the [[British Raj]].<ref>{{cite EB1911 |wstitle=Bombay Presidency |volume=4 |page=186}}</ref> It was the only state belonging to the Nasik Agency. Its capital was [[Surgana]] in [[Nashik District]] of present-day [[Maharashtra]].\n \nSurgana State's last ruler signed the accession to join the [[Indian Union]] in March 1948.\n\n== History ==\nSurgana State was founded towards the end of the 18th century. The territory of the state is [[mountainous]] and used to be inhabited mostly by [[Koli people|Koli]] [[kshatriya]]. The chiefs of Surgana were [[Maratha]] Kshatriya's from Malwa and the ancestors trace their genealogy to Parmar from [[Mount Abu]] and Rajasthan. They  prevented the [[Bhils]] and [[Kol people|Kol]] of [[Dang District, India|the Dangs]] from raiding [[Hatgadh Fort]] and the [[Western Ghats|ghats]]. They also provided military services to neighbouring 14 chiefs. They were titled as [[Deshmukh]] \"Desh\" means \"country\" and \"Mukh\" means \"mouth\" Spoke person of his country, of the [[Hatgadh Fort|Hatgadh]] division of Nasik which included the town of Surgana and other villages. They refused to pay tribute to the [[Maratha Empire|Maratha]]s and [[Mughal Empire|Mughal]]s so they were marked as rebel land (Bandi Mulk). Due to their strategic position between [[Surat]] and [[Deccan Plateau|Deccan]], Marathas made peace with them. In 1818, they attacked a British police party passing through their state. The British retaliated and captured the chief Malhar Rao and hanged him in 1819. So Surgana State became a [[British protectorate]] in 1818.<ref>[http://www.worldstatesmen.org/India_princes_K-W.html Princely States of India]</ref> The British made Bhikaji Rao as the new chief as he helped them against the Marathas. Bhikaji Rao was murdered in the riot caused by the mother of Malharrao and her brother-in-law, Pilaji. Pilaji was captured and executed by the British. The descendants of Malharrao were allowed the share in revenues of the state in 1846 and were granted an allowance grant in 1877. The chief of the state had powers to elect a Representative Member of the Chambers of Princes from 1921 to 1947. In March 1948, the last chief Dhairyashil Rao signed the Gujarat States Merger Agreement and ceded the state to Union of India.\n\nLater Dhairyashil Rao also served as the Member of the [[Rajya Sabha]] in 1952\u20131968 and 1972\u20131978.\n\nThe Princely State was bordered on the south by Peinth in Nasik, and in the west by the [[Bansda State|Bansda]] and [[Dharampur State]]s.\n\n===Rulers===\nThe rulers of the state bore the title '[[Deshmukh]]'. Surgana State's rulers belonged to the Hindu [[Pawar]] dynasty of [[Kshatriya]] [[Koli People|Kolis]].<ref>[http://indpaedia.com/ind/index.php/Surgana/view/surgana  Koli Provinces of India Surgana (Princely State)]</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/dli.csl.3300|page=[https://archive.org/details/dli.csl.3300/page/n517 612]|title=Gazetteer of the Bombay Presidency: Kh\u00e1ndesh|date=1880|publisher=Government Central Press|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Lethbridge|first=Sir Roper|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=7iOsNUZ2MXgC&pg=PA521&dq=Surgana+Golden+Boom&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj6pePZqbfoAhUX73MBHbVqA5wQ6AEIGzAA#v=onepage&q=Surgana%20Golden%20Boom&f=false|title=The Golden Book of India: A Genealogical and Biographical Dictionary of the Ruling Princes, Chiefs, Nobles, and Other Personages, Titled Or Decorated of the Indian Empire|date=2005|publisher=Aakar Books|isbn=978-81-87879-54-1|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gazetteers.maharashtra.gov.in/cultural.maharashtra.gov.in/english/gazetteer/Khandesh%20District/state_surgana.html#1|title=Maharashtra Gazetteer|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=KARR|first=G. B. SETON|url=http://archive.org/details/dli.bengal.10689.13419|title=ROUGH NOTES|date=1855|publisher=BOMBAY EDUCATION SOCIETY\u2019S PRESS, BOMBAY}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=vw4_AAAAYAAJ&pg=PA169&dq=Deshmooks+Kolee&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjp0vvLv7foAhUTjeYKHW2GCCMQ6AEIGzAA#v=onepage&q=Deshmooks%20Kolee&f=false|title=Selections from the Records of the Bombay Government|date=1856|publisher=Government at the Bombay Education Society's Press|language=en}}</ref>\n\n====Deshmukhs====\n*bf.1800 \u2013 1818             .....\n*1818 \u2013 1819                Malhar Rao                         (d. 1819) \n*1819 \u2013 1820                Bhikaji Rao \n*1820 \u2013 1854                Jashwant Rao I Bhikaji Rao \n*1854 \u2013 1867                Muvar Rao \n*1867 \u2013  2 Jun 1898         Shankar Rao Ravi Rao               (b. 1849 \u2013 d. ....) \n*1898 \u2013 22 Jun 1930         Pratap Rao Shankar Rao             (b. 18 Aug 1880 \u2013 d. 1930) \n*1930 \u2013 1936                Jashwant Rao II Pratap Rao         (b. 1902 \u2013 d. ....)\n*Apr 1936 \u2013 15 Aug 1947 (1948 \u2013 2003 titular)     Dhairyashil Rao Jashwant Rao     (b. 22 Nov 1922 \u2013 d. 23 Nov 2003)\n*2003 \u2013 present (titular)     Nitranjan Dhairyashil Rao\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Rajput dynasties and states]]\n*[[Political integration of India]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://members.iinet.net.au/~royalty/ips/s/surgana.html Surgana (Princely State)]\n{{Coord|20.57|N|73.62|E|region:IN-GU_type:city_source:kolossus-cawiki|display=title}}\n{{Princely states of the Baroda and Gujarat States Agency}}\n\n[[Category:Nashik district]]\n[[Category:Princely states of Maharashtra]]\n[[Category:Rajputs]]\n[[Category:Koli princely states]]\n", "name_user": "YaRaabAlHind", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eHistory)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Surgana_State"}
